From: Petr Wozniak <petr.wozniak@gmail.com>
Date: Tue, 19 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] xfrm: don't use GSO offload path for software SAs

xfrm_dev_offload_ok() returns true for software SAs (x->xso.dev == NULL)
because at the ok: label the guard "if (dev && ...)" evaluates false and
falls through to "return true".

This incorrectly routes SW SAs onto the GSO offload path:
  xfrm_output() → secpath_set() → esp4_gso_encap() (no encryption,
  just marks skb) → validate_xmit_xfrm() → esp_xmit() → MTK EIP
  async crypto → returns -EINPROGRESS → validate_xmit_xfrm returns NULL.

On real netdevs (eth, USB LTE modem) the TX path goes through
sch_direct_xmit() which handles NULL gracefully — async crypto
later delivers the encrypted packet via xfrm_dev_resume().

On bridge netdevs (noqueue qdisc) the TX path goes through the direct
branch of __dev_queue_xmit() where rc is initialized to -ENOMEM and
never overwritten when skb is NULL. This -ENOMEM propagates to userspace
as "sendmsg: Out of memory" on every packet.

Fix: when dev is NULL (SW SA, no HW offload device), return false so
the SA takes the normal inline encryption path in xfrm_output_one()
via esp4_output(). On -EINPROGRESS, xfrm_output_resume() converts it
to 0 (success), and the async callback re-enters xfrm_output_resume()
to deliver the encrypted packet.

HW offload SAs (dev != NULL) are unaffected — they still reach the
xdo_dev_offload_ok() check and the existing return true path.

Fixes: IPsec ENOMEM over bridge/wifi on platforms with async crypto
  engines (e.g. MediaTek MT7988A EIP).
Signed-off-by: Petr Wozniak <petr.wozniak@gmail.com>
---
 net/xfrm/xfrm_device.c | 3 +++
 1 file changed, 3 insertions(+)

--- a/net/xfrm/xfrm_device.c
+++ b/net/xfrm/xfrm_device.c
@@ -435,6 +435,9 @@ bool xfrm_dev_offload_ok(struct sk_buff *skb, struct xfrm_state *x)
 	}
 	return false;

 ok:
+	if (!dev)
+		return false;
+
 	if (dev && dev->xfrmdev_ops && dev->xfrmdev_ops->xdo_dev_offload_ok)
 		return x->xso.dev->xfrmdev_ops->xdo_dev_offload_ok(skb, x);

